ber of 1944, Private Eugene Becker served in the Italian Campaign and was killed in action near Florence on September 15, 1944; andWhereas, Kermit Becker was born July 20, 1918, in Maysville, West Virginia, the fifth child of Arnold and Ada Taylor Becker. He married Ruthlee Cade on May 20, 1941. On June 3, 1941, he entered the U. S. Army and became a military policeman. In March of 1943, he was promoted to Private First Class. He was stationed in Ireland and later fought in the North African Campaign. On September 4, 1943, while serving in Algeria, Private First Class Kermit Becker was attacked and sustained wounds that resulted in his death; andWhereas, It is fitting that an enduring memorial be established to commemorate U.S. Army Private Eugene Becker and his brother U.S. Army Private First Class Kermit Becker and their ultimate sacrifice for our state and country; therefore, be it Resolved by the Legislature of West Virginia:That the Division of Highways is hereby requested to name bridge number 12-028/07-012.02 (12A094), (39.12160, -79.21598) locally known as WEIMER BRIDGE, carrying CR 028/07 over NORTH FORK LUNICE CREEK in Grant County, the "U.S. Army PVT Eugene Becker and PFC Kermit Becker Memorial Bridge"; and, be it Further Resolved, That the Division of Highways is hereby requested to have made and be placed signs identifying the bridge as the “U.S. Army PVT Eugene Becker and PFC Kermit Becker Memorial Bridge”; and, be itFurther Resolved, That the Clerk of the Senate is hereby directed to forward a copy of this resolution to the Commissioner of the Division of Highways. Bill Status  | Bill Tracking  | Legacy WV Code  | Bulletin Board  | District Maps  | Senate Roster  | House Roster  | Live  | Blog  | Jobs  | Links  | Home This Web site is maintained by the West Virginia Legislature's Office of Reference & Information.  | Terms of Use | Webmaster | © 2025 West Virginia Legislature ** Print On Demand Name: Email: Phone: